    "question": "An MLX custom metal kernel accumulates a running sum of float16 values in a tight loop over 4096 elements. A numerical analyst flags this as a compliance risk for scientific workloads. Identify the specific mathematical failure mode, quantify why 4096 iterations makes it worse than 64, and state the minimal kernel change that mitigates it.",
    "reference_answer": "The risk is catastrophic cancellation and accumulated rounding error in float16. Float16 has ~3 decimal digits of precision and a maximum representable value of 65504. Summing 4096 terms of moderate magnitude causes the partial sum to dwarf individual increments, so small values are rounded to zero and never contribute — a form of severe loss of significance. With N=64 the relative error grows roughly as O(N·ε) where ε≈0.001 for float16; at N=4096 the error bound is 64× larger, easily corrupting the low-order bits of the result entirely. The minimal fix is pairwise (tree) summation or promoting the accumulator to float32 while keeping inputs as float16. In MLX Metal kernels, declare the accumulator as `float acc = 0.0f` (float32) and cast each float16 load before adding. This eliminates the growth of rounding error with N.",
